---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import CTAButton from '../components/CTAButton.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="MMTUK"
  description="Real Resource Economics and Modern Monetary Theory: MMTUK is the United Kingdom's first MMT-driven policy research organisation, producing policy papers and briefings, including proposals for a UK Job Guarantee."
>
  <p class="label">Related Work</p>
  <h1 class="mt-3">MMTUK</h1>

  <div class="mt-10 max-w-[44rem] space-y-10">
    <section>
      <h2 class="text-2xl">Real Resource Economics and MMT</h2>
      <p class="mt-3">
        Real Resource Economics aligns with the operational insights of Modern
        Monetary Theory (MMT): once you understand that a currency-issuing
        government is never financially constrained, the real questions become
        questions about resources (labour, materials, energy, time) and what we
        choose to do with them.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="text-2xl">What is Real Resource Economics?</h2>
      <p class="mt-3">
        Real Resource Economics treats the economy as a system bounded by people,
        materials, energy and time, not by money. Money is a tool the currency
        issuer creates to mobilise real resources towards public purposes; the
        binding constraints on policy are physical and social, not financial.
      </p>
      <p>
        For the policy research that sits alongside this work, see the MMTUK
        Policy Research Group, and the work of Richard Vague, Steve Keen, Richard
        Murphy, Bill Mitchell, Stephanie Kelton and Warren Mosler, and indeed
        all those cited in <em>The Money Sham</em> bibliography.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="text-2xl">About MMTUK</h2>
      <p class="mt-3">
        MMTUK is the United Kingdom’s first MMT-driven policy research
        organisation. It produces policy papers, briefings, and analysis that
        apply MMT to UK fiscal, monetary, and employment policy. Its flagship
        work includes detailed proposals for a UK Job Guarantee.
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <CTAButton href="https://mmtuk.org" external>Visit MMTUK</CTAButton>
      <CTAButton href="https://mmtuk.org/policy-papers/" external variant="outline">
        MMTUK Policy Papers
      </CTAButton>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
